# Docker Container Monitoring using JET and YANG

# About This Network Configuration Example

The objective of this NCE is to illustrate how to use the JET APIs on Junos devices to build a custom application. The NCE will demonstrate:

- Run Python applications with third party Python libraries onbox
- Collect operational state information from Junos using JET MGMT API
- Extend the Junos CLI to provide custom operation mode commands
- Publish application output similar to the output from a Junos operations mode command
- Demonstrate the ability to use XML RPC for the newly created operation mode command

This document includes examples with step-by-step instructions for configuring the device and servers to utilize JET APIs.

# Use Case Overview

This NCE addresses the use case where Network operators need the visibility into location of containers with respect to the network for troubleshooting. On any given network device, Network operators can run an operations mode command to identify the containers and the nodes connected to that switch. This information can be obtained either from the CLI or queried remotely using XML RPC.

# Technical Overview

### Docker Components

#### Docker Swarm

Docker Swarm is a clustering and scheduling tool for Docker containers. Swarm provides the ability to manage multiple Docker nodes as a single virtual system. Docker swarm provides the ability to manage hundreds of containers across multiple Docker nodes with features like load balancing and resource allocation based on utilization.

#### Docker Node

A **node** is an instance of the Docker engine participating in the swarm. A node is an instance of the Docker engine participating in the swarm. You can also think of this as a Docker node. You can run one or more nodes on a single physical computer or cloud server, but production swarm deployments typically include Docker nodes distributed across multiple physical and cloud machines.

To deploy your application to a swarm, you submit a service definition to a manager node. The manager node dispatches units of work called tasks to worker nodes.

Manager nodes also perform the orchestration and cluster management functions required to maintain the desired state of the swarm. Manager nodes elect a single leader to conduct orchestration tasks.

Worker nodes receive and execute tasks dispatched from manager nodes. By default manager nodes also run services as worker nodes, but you can configure them to run manager tasks exclusively and be manager-only nodes. An agent runs on each worker node and reports on the tasks assigned to it. The worker node notifies the manager node of the current state of its assigned tasks so that the manager can maintain the desired state of each worker.

Please refer to Docker documentation for details about the Docker components.

[https://docs.docker.com/engine/swarm/key-concepts/](https://docs.docker.com/engine/swarm/key-concepts/)



### QFX Switches

This could be any of the Junos QFX switches that is running software versions 17.1 or later.

## UseCase Workflow

Network operator trying to identify the containers that are attached to a particular switch can run the custom extended operation mode CLI command &quot;show docker containers&quot; on the switch. This custom command was created using the YANG infrastructure in Junos. Executing this command will trigger the cmonitor.py script.

The cmonitor.py script running on the box performs the following tasks

- --Query the QFX switch using JET APIs to identify the LLDP neighbors on the switch
- --Use the docker.py modules to query the Docker Swarm manager node to get the list of containers and the worker nodes on which these containers are located
- --Match the LLDP neighbor information from QFX switches with the worker node information received from the Swarm manager node
- --Identify the list of containers that are attached directly to this QFX switch
- --The script will render the collected information to the screen like a regular Junos show command output

# Configuration Example

## Introduction

This configuration example will illustrate step-by-step procedure to configure QFX switch to run a JET application, create custom operation mode CLI and publish the results in Junos CLI. This document will not provide all the details for configuring Docker Swarm Manager node or Worker nodes. This information is well documented in Docker documentation

## Demo components used in this example

This example uses the following hardware and software components:

- --QFX5100 Switch running Junos OS Release 17.2R1
- --One Ubuntu server as Docker Manager node (17.03.1-ce)
- --One Ubuntu server as Docker Worker node (17.03.1-ce)
- --One Centos server as Docker Worker node (17.09.0-ce)

## Overview and Topology

## Configuration

### Linux and Docker Configuration

1. Configure the linux servers (all three)

- --Follow the step to install Docker-ce on Ubuntu and Centos

[https://docs.docker.com/engine/installation/linux/docker-ce/ubuntu/#install-using-the-repository](https://docs.docker.com/engine/installation/linux/docker-ce/ubuntu/#install-using-the-repository)

- --Run &quot;sudo apt-get install lldpd&quot; on Ubuntu or &quot;sudo yum install lldpd&quot; on Centos to install LLDPd
- --Run &quot;lldpd&quot; to start the daemon

1. Configure the Swarm Manager node

- --Start the docker daemon with exposed ports: &quot;dockerd H 0.0.0.0:2375 H /var/run/docker.sock&quot;
- --If you receive the error &quot;Error starting daemon: pid file found, ensure docker is not running or delete /var/run/docker.pid&quot; then run &quot;ps aux | grep docker&quot;
- --Run &quot;sudo kill -9 [pid]&quot; where [pid] are the process IDs of the docker services
- --Rerun the original command
- --Run &quot;docker swarm init&quot; to start the swarm manager
- --Copy the swarm join token given by the output of the terminal and paste it on the docker worker nodes so they can join the swarm
  - docker swarm join --token SWMTKN-1-0foquq291mol3uxq8hbwesdmac3bqnjldmxd0amzs83mxdbpcl-94ryoq9u4ccv70tmyegy2xhpc 10.97.71.233:2377
- --Services can be deployed to the swarm using &quot;docker service create --replicas 1 --name helloworld alpine ping docker.com&quot;

Please refer to Docker swarm documentation for detailed documentation on deploying docker nodes and swarm cluster.

[https://docs.docker.com/engine/swarm/](https://docs.docker.com/engine/swarm/)

1. Copy the necessary JET API modules for this use case

1. Extend the Operation mode CLI using YANG support infrastructure in Junos

We can add new configurational and operational knobs using the custom UI extensions. In this example, we will see how to add a custom operation mode CLI and RPCs for Junos. The new operational command and RPCs require a YANG file and a corresponding action script file.

- --Copy the necessary files for extending the CLI

From git clone, copy the &quot;py/cmonitor.py&quot; script and &quot;rpc-docker-containers.yang&quot; YANG module onto the QFX5100 into /var/tmp/docker-jet directory

- --Defining the new CLIs through YANG file

The new operational command will be added through a YANG file. In this YANG file, we define the inputs and output format of the new RPC that we are introducing. The input container defined in the YANG file will be the arguments that will be provided by the operational command or RPC. The output format will contain the template which will be used by JUNOS infra to display the output from the action script. Please note, the action script should provide output in XML format.

module rpc-docker-containers {

  namespace &quot;http://YANG.juniper.net/examples/rpc-cli&quot;;

  prefix rpc-cli;

  import junos-extension {

    prefix junos;

  }

  import junos-extension-odl {

    prefix junos-odl;

  }

  organization

    &quot;Juniper Networks, Inc.&quot;;

  description

    &quot;Docker Container Monitoring Tool&quot;;

  rpc get-docker-containers {

     description &quot;Show all running containers&quot;;

     junos:command &quot;show docker containers&quot;;

     junos:action-execute {

       junos:script &quot;cmonitor.py&quot;;

     }



    output {

      container docker-container-info {

        container container-info {

          leaf hostname {

            type string;

            description &quot;Hostname of node running the container&quot;;

          }

          leaf service {

            type string;

            description &quot;Name of service&quot;;

          }

          leaf containerID {

            type string;

            description &quot;First 16 chars of container ID&quot;;

          }

          leaf port {

            type string;

            description &quot;Exposed ports from inside container to host&quot;;

          }

          leaf socketRemote {

            type string;

            description &quot;Node port that connects to device&quot;;

          }

          leaf socketHost {

            type string;

            description &quot;Device port that connects to node&quot;;

          }

          container container-info-format {

            junos-odl:cli-format;

            junos-odl:header &quot;NODE\t\t   SERVICE NAME\t  CONTAINER ID\t     PORTS\t    SWITCH PHYSICAL PORT  SERVER PHYSICAL PORT\n&quot;;

            junos-odl:picture &quot;@&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; @||||||||||||| @||||||||||||||||| @||||||||||||| @|||||||||||||  @&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&quot;;

            junos-odl:line {

              junos-odl:field &quot;hostname&quot;;

              junos-odl:field &quot;service&quot;;

              junos-odl:field &quot;containerID&quot;;

              junos-odl:field &quot;port&quot;;

              junos-odl:field &quot;socketRemote&quot;;

              junos-odl:field &quot;socketHost&quot;;

            }

        }

    }

    }

  }

  }

}



Define the action script for this operation command. In this case the action script calls the &quot;cmonitor.py&quot; script. The action script should output the data in xml format and tags should match the output description we provided in the input YANG file. Execute the following commands to map the YANG file to the action script.

request system yang add package docker-rpc module [/var/tmp/docker-jet/rpc-docker-containers.yang /var/tmp/docker-jet/junos-extension.yang /var/tmp/docker-jet/junos-extension-odl.yang] action-script /var/tmp/docker-jet/cmonitor.py
